  <static seed="1458" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations55.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {-\frac{6}{y}-\frac{8}{y-5}} = 3 }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{\frac{10}{3},-3\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of fractions, we multiply each term in this equation by the common denominator, which is <m>{y\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)}</m> in this example.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp {-\frac{6}{y}-\frac{8}{y-5}} = 3 \\
   \amp {-\frac{6}{y}y\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)-\frac{8}{y-5}y\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)} ={3y\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)} \\
   \amp {-6\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)-8y} = {3y^{2}-15y} \\
   \amp {-6y+30-8y} = {3y^{2}-15y} \\
   \amp {-14y+30} = {3y^{2}-15y} \\
   \amp {-14y+30-3y^{2}+15y} = 0 \\
   \amp {-3y^{2}+y+30} = 0 \\
   \amp -({3y^{2}-y-30})=0 \\
   \amp -({y+3})({3y-10})=0 \\
   \amp {y+3}=0 \:\: or\:\: {3y-10}=0 \\
   \amp y={-3} \:\: or\:\: y={{\frac{10}{3}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p><alert>Checking</alert></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp y = 0 \amp \;\amp  y - 5=0 \\
   \amp y=0 \amp \;\amp  y=5
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must exclude <m>0</m> and <m>5</m> from the solution set. There is no conflict with those two solutions we got, so the final solution is <m>y={-3}</m> and <m>y={{\frac{10}{3}}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
